	  <tr id="abs_Shaban21A" class="abstract noshow">
            <td colspan="4" ><div align="justify"> <b>Abstract</b>: In this paper, we focus on the problem of estimating the traversability of terrain for autonomous off-road navigation.  To produce dense and accurate local traversability maps, a robot must reason about geometric and semantic properties of the environment. %Traditional approaches usually focus on only one aspect of the problem, but we argue that these three aspects are closely connected and should be learned jointly. 

			To achieve this goal, we develop a novel Bird's Eye View Network (BEVNet), a deep neural network that directly predicts dense traversability maps from sparse LiDAR inputs. BEVNet processes both geometric and semantic information in a temporally consistent fashion. More importantly, it uses learned prior and history to \emph{predict} traversability in unseen space and into the future, allowing a robot to better appraise its situation. We quantitatively evaluate BEVNet on both on-road and off-road scenarios, and show that it outperforms a variety of strong baselines.
